reasoning: Well, the first thing I do is make sure I’m inside my circle of competence, and alphabet soup of algorithms and advertising auctions isn’t something I understand thoroughly—outside my wheelhouse. As for a moat, Google certainly has one around search and ad‐tech, but I can’t measure its durability without financials. Management quality and capital allocation? Again, insufficient data prevents me from sizing up those stewards; I’d want to see track records of honest, owner‐minded decision making. The balance sheet, earnings consistency and debt levels are a blank page here, so I can’t judge the financial fortress. Intrinsic value? No numbers to work with means no margin of safety. Long term, you’d think a dominant search franchise might endure, but rapid technological change and regulatory scrutiny are red flags. Compared to the likes of Coca-Cola or See’s Candies—businesses I know inside and out—this is a pass. I’ve found it best to say ‘no’ if I don’t fully grasp the business. I’ll stick with what I understand and pass on GOOG for now.
